codex
The top infra task from the repo’s source of truth was `Monitor disk usage`, not `Run security audit`: the latest infra logs and artifacts on March 9, 2026 had already shifted to disk pressure, with `/` at `100%` used and runs `44` through `55` prioritizing that task.

I hardened the disk-reporting path in [tools/infra_disk.py](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/tools/infra_disk.py) and added regression coverage in [tests/test_infra_disk.py](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/tests/test_infra_disk.py). The change is safe and review-first: when root pressure is high, infra reports now also surface the largest paths under `/home/ubuntu` instead of stopping at `/var/cache`, `~/.cache`, and journals. The new artifact now exposes the real hidden consumers driving the incident: `~/.gradle` (`2.3G`), `~/.gradle/caches` (`1.9G`), and `~/.npm-global` (`1.8G`), without turning them into blind cleanup actions.

Verification passed:
- `python3 -m unittest tests.test_infra_disk tests.test_infra_status`
- `python3 -m py_compile tools/infra_disk.py tools/infra-status.py tools/infra-autopilot.py tools/infra_tmp_cleanup.py`
- `python3 tools/infra-status.py`
- `python3 tools/department-commands.py run infra`

Latest generated evidence:
- [20260309T123252Z-r55-monitor-disk-usage-alert-if-80.md](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/departments/infra/artifacts/checks/20260309T123252Z-r55-monitor-disk-usage-alert-if-80.md)
- [20260309T123254Z-infra-status.md](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/departments/infra/artifacts/checks/20260309T123254Z-infra-status.md)

The live blocker remains unchanged: root is still at `100%` on March 9, 2026, so actual space reclamation still needs a deliberate cleanup pass on the host. The same status artifact also still shows unexpected external listeners and missing host-firewall visibility. I recorded the session in [departments/infra/MEMORY.md](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/departments/infra/MEMORY.md) and [memory/2026-03-09.md](/home/ubuntu/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-03-09.md).
